the trees because there was so much to do. 

189
00:15:19,960 --> 00:15:25,120
And so that was a situation that I didn't 
really understand how to navigate at that  

190
00:15:25,120 --> 00:15:28,960
point in my career. And there were two 
or three manager changes concurrently,  

191
00:15:29,680 --> 00:15:33,840
and so I didn't have a manager to lean on that 
I felt like I had a relationship with to help me  

192
00:15:33,840 --> 00:15:39,280
to navigate that space. And I felt like the scope 
was actually too much for what needed to be done,  

193
00:15:39,280 --> 00:15:43,280
and so I needed to find a better kind of fit 
for me. There was nothing wrong with the team,  

194
00:15:43,280 --> 00:15:48,200
it was a great learning environment, 
but it was the confluence of scope  

195
00:15:48,200 --> 00:15:53,160
and manager and all happening at 
once just wasn't a good fit for me.

196
00:15:53,160 --> 00:15:57,600
A lot of people are in these situations 
where they'd say they go through this score,  

197
00:15:57,600 --> 00:16:01,320
they identify I have way too little scope, 
way too much scope like you described,  

198
00:16:01,320 --> 00:16:05,000
and there's always this question of can I 
actually make a change or is this just not,  

199
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:09,000
am I not in a position? Especially, I see 
product managers, there's just always a lot of,  

200
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:12,840
I can't actually change anything. What 
do you often tell people around this that  

201
00:16:12,840 --> 00:16:17,040
just feel like there's nothing I can do here 
and my manager sucks, what am I going to do?

202
00:16:17,040 --> 00:16:21,560
Well, I do think one of the things that I 
recognize is your manager. Not all of these  

203
00:16:21,560 --> 00:16:27,960
variables is created equal and the manager is 
the most important variable in the environment,  

204
00:16:27,960 --> 00:16:34,720
because a great manager who is empathetic, 
who is aware of what's going on, who is a  

205
00:16:34,720 --> 00:16:41,360
great communicator, has the ability to move the 
chess pieces around and to fix some of these for  

206
00:16:41,360 --> 00:16:47,600
you either immediately or in time. There's no 
one other than your manager who can really help  

207
00:16:47,600 --> 00:16:52,040
to increase your scope or to help make sure 
that the team has the right pieces in place,  

208
00:16:52,040 --> 00:16:55,920
or dial in some of the issues 
that you might see in culture. 

209
00:16:55,920 --> 00:16:58,840
And so that is why people say they 
don't leave a job, they leave a manager  

210
00:16:59,440 --> 00:17:04,400
because the manager is the one that has a lot of 
the power to fix a lot of these variables. And so  

211
00:17:04,400 --> 00:17:10,480
really the question becomes like to what extent 
have you been able to clearly articulate what are  

212
00:17:10,480 --> 00:17:15,240
the... And dispassionately articulate, what are 
the challenges that you're having, you're seeing  

213
00:17:15,240 --> 00:17:20,360
across some of these variables with your manager? 
Help them to tie it back to how it's impacting  

214
00:17:20,360 --> 00:17:27,880
your work and see if they can help you to 
create a plan to alleviate some of these things.

215
00:17:27,880 --> 00:17:31,160
That's super interesting. Then your experience 
with the manager is kind of the core of a lot  

216
00:17:31,160 --> 00:17:35,160
of these variables. Is there anything you 
recommend to people if their managers is  

217
00:17:35,160 --> 00:17:39,560
not someone they like, is it just try to 
find a new manager or potentially leave?

218
00:17:39,560 --> 00:17:42,320
You're never going to always like your 
manager, right? That's not the... The  

219
00:17:42,320 --> 00:17:46,800
goal isn't to like your manager. Ideally, 
you respect them and they respect you, you  

220
00:17:46,800 --> 00:17:51,480
feel like there's things that you can learn from 
them. Finding a new manager is always an option,  

221
00:17:51,480 --> 00:17:55,720
but I guess sometimes the real question is, is 
actually spending time to try to understand what  

222
00:17:55,720 --> 00:18:02,880
is your manager optimizing? A lot of times I think 
there is a big disconnect between an IC focusing  

223
00:18:02,880 --> 00:18:08,440
on their discrete area and try to optimize 
for local maxima, versus understanding, okay,  

224
00:18:08,440 --> 00:18:14,840
my manager's thinking about these things and this 
is how I fit in, and understanding maybe they have  

225
00:18:14,840 --> 00:18:20,320
a gap to understanding why your area is important. 
Or maybe there's stuff that's on your manager's  

226
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:24,320
plate that is actually adjacent to your remit that 
if you understood that they were optimizing for,  

227
00:18:24,320 --> 00:18:27,760
you can take that on and you would find more 
synergies with what they're trying to do.

228
00:18:27,760 --> 00:18:28,760
I love that advice.  

229
00:18:29,360 --> 00:18:32,360
Let's talk about the other side of this 
equation. We've talked about environment,  

230
00:18:32,360 --> 00:18:37,440
let's talk about skills. What do you advise there 
for folks that want to improve their skills?

231
00:18:37,440 --> 00:18:43,040
The skills part is really, really big and it's 
something that requires I think, consistent  

232
00:18:43,040 --> 00:18:49,400
evolution of your own abilities. And so I broke it 
out in that blog post kind of communication, your  

233
00:18:49,400 --> 00:18:55,240
ability to influence your leadership, strategic 
thinking and then execution, actually getting  

234
00:18:55,240 --> 00:18:59,680
things done. The communication above these, 
again, not all of these are created equal. I think  

235
00:18:59,680 --> 00:19:07,160
communication is the one that tends to be the most 
impactful. And you see this in a lot of ways. You  

236
00:19:07,160 --> 00:19:11,080
see this for people who are poor executors 
but incredible communicators and they seem  

237
00:19:11,080 --> 00:19:15,560
to continue to rise and rise because they can tell 
a great story, but when you look under the covers,  

238
00:19:15,560 --> 00:19:20,320
there's nothing there. There's no substance there.
So communication for better or worse is one of  

239
00:19:20,320 --> 00:19:24,320
the most important things. But building out 
your skills I think is really just kind of a,  

240
00:19:24,320 --> 00:19:29,880
it is an interesting time to be in product and 
to be in tech right now because you have so many  

241
00:19:29,880 --> 00:19:35,240
more ways to build out your skills than what 
previously existed. Just so many incredible  

242
00:19:35,240 --> 00:19:39,400
blog posts like your podcasts and blogs, 
there's so many incredible people who've  

243
00:19:39,400 --> 00:19:43,960
come on here who tell you things like how 
to go to market, how to think about B2B SaaS  

244
00:19:43,960 --> 00:19:51,400
and metrics. And so listening to you, reading 
Ben Thompson, understanding his mental models,  

245
00:19:51,400 --> 00:19:56,520
if you go to look at Elena Verner or whoever, 
there's so many thought leaders who are out there. 

246
00:19:56,520 --> 00:20:01,760
So I think being a voracious reader is really, 
really critical because it helps to build your  

247
00:20:01,760 --> 00:20:06,680
toolkit and you need arrows in your quiver to 
really understand how to think about the right  

248
00:20:06,680 --> 00:20:11,920
framework and the right mentor at the right time.
One thing I also tell people is people think about  

249
00:20:11,920 --> 00:20:18,320
mentorship as like, I have a mentor, Lenny is 
my mentor, or John is my mentor. I tell them,  

250
00:20:18,320 --> 00:20:23,520
it's actually better to have a stable of mentors. 
You want to have three or four. And ideally,  

251
00:20:23,520 --> 00:20:28,640
what you do is you meet with each one of them 
once a month on a different Friday of the month.  

252
00:20:29,360 --> 00:20:32,040
And so you might have three or four people 
on every Friday you're meeting with someone  

253
00:20:32,040 --> 00:20:35,240
different. And the reason why this is so 
important is because if you, Lenny, are  

254
00:20:35,240 --> 00:20:39,880
a mentor to me and you're busy one Friday and we 
only meet once a month now I don't have anyone to  

255
00:20:39,880 --> 00:20:44,760
talk to for two months. And you're going through a 
lot of things and you're not really able to bounce  

256
00:20:44,760 --> 00:20:50,400
ideas, or build skills or learn how influence 
others, but if you have three or four mentors,  

257
00:20:51,520 --> 00:20:55,480
you have someone different to talk to every week. 
And if one or two of them cancel, you still have  

258
00:20:55,480 --> 00:21:01,280
two people to talk to that month and you still 
can continue to grow and to build your thinking. 

259
00:21:01,280 --> 00:21:05,480
So that's something I always recommend. And 
then the last thing I actually talk about is,  

260
00:21:05,480 --> 00:21:12,000
when it comes to execution, I think people don't, 
especially product managers, don't do enough of  

261
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:18,160
watching and learning from others. There's an art 
and a science to product management. And in a lot  

262
00:21:18,160 --> 00:21:22,960
of ways I come from a background of education and 
in a lot of ways in product management, it's very  

263
00:21:22,960 --> 00:21:27,800
similar. You want to watch how well the people 
hone their craft, how they deliver, how they  

264
00:21:27,800 --> 00:21:33,000
lead teams and kind of steal things from them. 
Figure out, well, wow, Lenny did this really,  

265
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:36,920
really well when he was at Airbnb. It was really 
incredible. I'm going to take that. I'm going to  

266
00:21:36,920 --> 00:21:42,120
take how he runs that team, or how he landed that 
framework, or how he communicated this message  

267
00:21:42,120 --> 00:21:47,800
and note it and use it in my own toolkit later on. 
And so if you're really a student of product, you  

268
00:21:47,800 --> 00:21:52,040
can't just be a student of theory, you've got to 
be a student of practice too, meaning you're going  

269
00:21:52,040 --> 00:21:56,240
and you're looking, it's like, "Hey, I'd love 
to sit in your team meetings. Can I come watch?  

270
00:21:56,240 --> 00:22:00,720
Or your PM meetings or your leadership meetings." 
And you are really like doing that for the sake of  

271
00:22:00,720 --> 00:22:04,720
learning is really, really incredible. And that's 
some of the ways I talk about building skills.

272
00:22:04,720 --> 00:22:08,880
Is there an example of that latter lesson 
that you learned from someone that comes  

273
00:22:08,880 --> 00:22:13,400
to mind of watching someone and 
like, oh, I'm going to do that.

274
00:22:13,400 --> 00:22:21,320
Earlier in my career, when I first got to 
Instagram, I wasn't the first Growth PM,  

275
00:22:21,320 --> 00:22:26,440
but I was one of the first and a guy who was there 
before me, his name was Georgia Lee, he actually  

276
00:22:26,440 --> 00:22:31,840
stood up the growth team and ended up leaving six 
months right after I joined. But I watched, George  

277
00:22:31,840 --> 00:22:38,800
was a really good listener. He had just a really 
incredible ability to be in a room and hear what  

278
00:22:38,800 --> 00:22:44,800
was going on, to recast it back and make sure that 
everyone felt good about where we were and what  

279
00:22:44,800 --> 00:22:52,960
was being said and the path forward, and really 
crystallizing the action items and also how people  

280
00:22:52,960 --> 00:22:58,440
felt about what the next steps were. And walking 
out of that meeting, it felt like he always had  

281
00:22:59,120 --> 00:23:04,280
buy-in and clarity and was helpful to 
build trust. You can see him almost  

282
00:23:04,280 --> 00:23:11,480
winning trust in every moment of that meeting. 
And that was something that I really admired,  

283
00:23:11,480 --> 00:23:15,480
and learned, and kind sought to 
emulate later on in my career.

284
00:23:15,480 --> 00:23:18,600
That's an awesome example. It comes back to the 
skill of communication that you talked about,  

285
00:23:18,600 --> 00:23:23,200
just the power becoming really good at that. And 
this is such a simple skill you just described,  

286
00:23:23,200 --> 00:23:26,200
is just recapping, here's what we talked 
about. Here's what we're going to do.  

287
00:23:26,200 --> 00:23:30,400
Here's the decisions we made. Here's action 
items. It's not actually difficult, it's just-

288
00:23:30,400 --> 00:23:35,080
It's not, actually. But what was magical about the 
way he did it. It's like he would name people and  

289
00:23:35,080 --> 00:23:40,520
their contributions and show how all of this 
came together into what is the path forward.

290
00:23:41,280 --> 00:23:41,680
That is amazing.

291
00:23:41,680 --> 00:23:44,960
And it's the communication, but it's 
also the other side. It's the other coin,  

292
00:23:44,960 --> 00:23:49,760
the side of communication, which is eliciting to 
figure out how you communicate back to others.

293
00:23:49,760 --> 00:23:53,480
So good. Following up on something else 
you talked about, which is mentors. Anytime  

294
00:23:53,480 --> 00:23:58,200
someone talks about finding mentors, everyone's 
always, how do I find a mentor? What advice do  

295
00:23:58,200 --> 00:24:03,360
you share with folks of how to find a mentor 
to help? You say once a week or once a month?

296
00:24:03,360 --> 00:24:10,040
Where I see people find the most success is they 
ask. They tell people what they're working on or  

297
00:24:10,040 --> 00:24:16,320
what challenges they have and they say, "Do you 
know someone who I might be able to learn from  

298
00:24:16,320 --> 00:24:21,320
who has done this or has good thinking about this 
recently?" So instead of just going to someone  

299
00:24:21,320 --> 00:24:25,160
saying, "Hey, can you be a mentor?" Coming to 
me and say, "Hey, Bengaly, I'm actually trying  

300
00:24:25,160 --> 00:24:29,440
to figure out how do I change the way this team 
operates because we need to go from this model  

301
00:24:29,440 --> 00:24:34,320
to that model, but here's some of the challenges. 
So do you know someone who's actually really good  

302
00:24:34,320 --> 00:24:40,480
at changing the way teams work or really good at 
communicating a new vision that I can talk to?" 

303
00:24:40,480 --> 00:24:47,080
And so that I think is really important 
because what you do is you're creating a seed,  

304
00:24:47,080 --> 00:24:51,960
and the seed is there's a triad and you have the 
person who's looking for the mentor. You have  

305
00:24:51,960 --> 00:24:57,120
the recommender, the recommender, and then you 
have the potential mentor. And the recommender  

306
00:24:57,120 --> 00:25:01,520
is basically saying, "Here, there's common 
purpose between the two of you and I can see it,  

307
00:25:01,520 --> 00:25:05,960
and I think this is important, so I want 
you all to come together." And that triad  

308
00:25:05,960 --> 00:25:10,960
in that moment creates a higher affinity, 
highly likelihood that the person who needs  

309
00:25:10,960 --> 00:25:15,600
the help and the person who you're connecting 
them with are going to see mutual benefit from  

310
00:25:15,600 --> 00:25:22,160
one another. And I think I find that just doing 
that and seeding that and being really focused  

311
00:25:22,160 --> 00:25:27,040
on what the opportunity or the challenge is, 
tends to lead to better connections as opposed  

312
00:25:27,040 --> 00:25:30,160
to just reaching out and saying, "Hey, I 
like your style. Will you be my mentor?"

313
00:25:30,160 --> 00:25:34,200
So essentially share with folks you 
trust, here's what I'm working on.  

314
00:25:34,200 --> 00:25:37,640
See if they recommend someone that could 
help you with that specific skill versus  

315
00:25:37,640 --> 00:25:40,680
assuming that there's this person 
that can help you with this skill?

316
00:25:40,680 --> 00:25:41,200
That's right.

317
00:25:41,200 --> 00:25:44,560
I love it. Going back to your advice on career,  

318
00:25:44,560 --> 00:25:49,320
something that you wrote about in your post 
plus folks have told me you're really big on,  

319
00:25:49,320 --> 00:25:53,000
is this something you call understand 
work? Does that ring a bell?

320
00:25:53,000 --> 00:25:53,640
Yes, it does.

321
00:25:53,640 --> 00:25:56,080
Okay. Talk about that and why that's important?

322
00:25:56,080 --> 00:25:58,360
I certainly cannot take credit 
for understand work. This  

323
00:25:58,360 --> 00:26:00,240
is part of an old Facebook framework of 
understand, identify, execute. What I-

324
00:26:00,240 --> 00:26:06,360
Facebook framework of understand, identify, 
execute. What I probably will say is I guess I've  

325
00:26:06,360 --> 00:26:11,200
been the shepherd for understand work in other 
companies. I've taken it from my time at Facebook  

326
00:26:11,200 --> 00:26:16,840
and Relink Institute or rigorously at Instagram, 
then at Instacart and when I helped with Twitter,  

327
00:26:16,840 --> 00:26:22,960
now at YouTube. The way I like to talk about 
it with my teams is that first I tell a story  

328
00:26:22,960 --> 00:26:28,240
actually, and the story is we've all had a moment 
where we have worked on something with a team,  

329
00:26:29,160 --> 00:26:35,400
super excited, finally it launches and we go out 
to dinner and we celebrate. And we're celebrating,  

330
00:26:35,400 --> 00:26:40,400
everyone's juiced. It's great night. You go 
back to the office the next day and you look  

331
00:26:40,400 --> 00:26:44,840
at the metrics and the metrics are flat 
and everyone's a little bummed. Why did  

332
00:26:44,840 --> 00:26:49,360
this happen? Right. Why are the metrics 
flat? What happened? We worked so hard. 

333
00:26:49,360 --> 00:26:53,640
And ultimately when you unpack it, you realize 
that you built something that you thought was  

334
00:26:53,640 --> 00:26:59,920
going to be a good idea, but you really didn't 
understand a lot of key components of what people  

335
00:26:59,920 --> 00:27:06,200
really needed, what pain points really existed, 
or what were the alternatives and what the real  

336
00:27:06,200 --> 00:27:10,760
value of those alternatives were in the market, or 
exactly how the product needed to work, what the  

337
00:27:10,760 --> 00:27:17,000
flywheel or what the experience needed to be. And 
so that is what I call the anti-pattern of what we  

338
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:22,480
want to do and I call that identify, justify, 
execute. Right. Where you identify something,  

339
00:27:22,480 --> 00:27:26,040
someone says, "Hey, you know what? This would 
be great to build." And you identify that,  

340
00:27:26,040 --> 00:27:30,800
then you go pull data to go justify why that 
would be great to build and then you sink an  

341
00:27:30,800 --> 00:27:36,400
ungodly amount of time working on it in order to 
make it work, but it ultimately doesn't succeed. 

342
00:27:36,400 --> 00:27:40,240
And that is the anti-pattern to what is kind 
of like the Facebook kind of way of thinking,  

343
00:27:40,240 --> 00:27:44,920
which is understand, identify, execute, right? 
So first you have to really understand from  

344
00:27:44,920 --> 00:27:49,240
first principles what is actually going 
on. So when we talk about understand work,  

345
00:27:49,240 --> 00:27:58,400
there's a few ways to think about it. One is, it 
is an intentional affordance in your execution  

346
00:27:58,400 --> 00:28:03,840
to do the work that helps you to de-risk a 
project and to learn what's going on. When  

347
00:28:03,840 --> 00:28:08,920
I say an intentional affordance, meaning you put 
it down like Lenny is going to work on this thing.  

348
00:28:08,920 --> 00:28:13,680
Right. Lenny as a product manager is going to 
write a strategy. Janice as a designer is going  

349
00:28:13,680 --> 00:28:18,840
to design a prototype, whatever the thing is, and 
you put it down as actual an item as opposed to  

350
00:28:18,840 --> 00:28:23,120
assuming it's going to happen in the background. 
We don't make an affordance for understand work,  

351
00:28:23,120 --> 00:28:27,240
then the work doesn't get done and 
everyone's just sprinting on execution. 

352
00:28:27,240 --> 00:28:33,360
And so it's a planned intentional time to 
the team's bandwidth to figure out what is  

353
00:28:33,360 --> 00:28:38,200
it that we need to do to understand what's 
happening. And so for example at Instagram  

354
00:28:38,200 --> 00:28:43,680
we did a lot of understand work of what makes 
for a good connection? Right. How do we want  

355
00:28:43,680 --> 00:28:47,360
to think about that? How do we want to make 
sure that we're actually growing a graph,  

356
00:28:47,360 --> 00:28:52,440
a social graph that makes sense? And so I might 
work with data science to do understand work,  

357
00:28:52,440 --> 00:28:59,200
to pull a funnel and look at the different types 
of connections for different types of users and  

358
00:28:59,200 --> 00:29:05,600
make it make sense. Right. And engineering might 
do understand work to instrument logging to make  

359
00:29:05,600 --> 00:29:10,120
sure that we have the data that we need 
in order to tell the story. And so you're  

360
00:29:10,120 --> 00:29:15,160
doing this understand work to basically better 
understand the gaps in knowledge. What's also  

361
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:20,840
really interesting is that understand work helps 
you to clarify what is a root cause, or what is a  

362
00:29:20,840 --> 00:29:29,320
job to be done, or what is the right use case?
And because the team adopts this mentality,  

363
00:29:29,320 --> 00:29:34,360
it becomes this forcing function for execution. So 
when someone says, "You know what we should build?  

364
00:29:34,360 --> 00:29:40,880
We should build this." You have a team that's 
enabled and empowered to say, "That's a good idea,  

365
00:29:40,880 --> 00:29:46,240
but we don't actually understand these three 
things before we start working on that. So maybe  

366
00:29:46,240 --> 00:29:52,160
we should do understand work to make sure that 
that is actually the right idea." Right. And so  

367
00:29:52,160 --> 00:29:59,080
what you end up getting by embracing this concept 
is two things. You get parallel paths of work. So  

368
00:29:59,080 --> 00:30:04,200
every sprint, let's say you do a three-week sprint 
or a three-month roadmap, you're executing on the  

369
00:30:04,200 --> 00:30:09,760
things that you have a lot of conviction around 
and you're also doing understand work in parallel.  

370
00:30:09,760 --> 00:30:15,000
And so at the end of the sprint you have learnings 
from what you executed. Wow, that test or that  

371
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:19,440
launch worked really well. We should double down. 
Or Wow, that test or launch didn't work. Here's  

