1127
01:32:49,760 --> 01:32:52,320
Do you have a favorite interview question that you  

1128
01:32:52,320 --> 01:32:54,720
like to ask candidates when 
you're interviewing them?

1129
01:32:54,720 --> 01:33:01,320
I've got a relatively new one that I love. 
This works exceptionally well I believe  

1130
01:33:01,320 --> 01:33:06,720
for more senior hires, whether they're 
like group product managers, directors,  

1131
01:33:06,720 --> 01:33:13,520
or even kind of senior ICs. I go through and 
I think about what are the four, usually five  

1132
01:33:13,520 --> 01:33:20,720
skills that are really critical for someone to 
have in this job. And I think about them myself  

1133
01:33:20,720 --> 01:33:28,160
and I think about the archetypes of what is the 
ratio I want of these? But then I ask them, I say,  

1134
01:33:28,160 --> 01:33:32,480
Hey, take out a piece of paper or take out your 
laptop. I'm going to give you five skills and I  

1135
01:33:32,480 --> 01:33:39,160
want you to stack-rank them for me. One to five. 
So one being the one you're strongest at and five  

1136
01:33:39,160 --> 01:33:43,000
being the one you're relatively weakest at.
So it's way better than saying give me your  

1137
01:33:43,000 --> 01:33:48,280
strengths and weaknesses. It also forces them 
to contextualize it against the skills that  

1138
01:33:48,280 --> 01:33:54,040
you're looking for, but it also helps you have 
a meaningful conversation around how they think  

1139
01:33:54,040 --> 01:33:58,600
about themselves and their self-awareness and to 
what extent they're ranking these skills based on  

1140
01:33:58,600 --> 01:34:03,720
the context they're in versus their own ability.
Sometimes you rank something a five because  

1141
01:34:04,320 --> 01:34:07,680
something you would just weak at because you 
haven't had to do because there's a strong  

1142
01:34:07,680 --> 01:34:12,160
function at that company. And so when 
they stack-rank it and then people are  

1143
01:34:12,160 --> 01:34:16,800
like ... I've asked this probably four or five 
times on a recent role. I hire people like, Ooh,  

1144
01:34:16,800 --> 01:34:23,720
this is really hard. But really good question. 
I usually will dig into what is number two and  

1145
01:34:23,720 --> 01:34:28,920
what's number four and number five, and why? And 
it really helps me to one, calibrate am I looking  

1146
01:34:28,920 --> 01:34:33,400
for the right person? And two, are their skills 
actually a match for what we need at this time?

1147
01:34:33,400 --> 01:34:37,520
I love when I hear a question I've never 
heard before. That is genius. Next question,  

1148
01:34:37,520 --> 01:34:41,240
do you have a favorite product you've 
recently discovered that you really like?

1149
01:34:41,240 --> 01:34:46,080
I think one that I enjoy quite a lot ... 
Actually, it's really kind of ... It's  

1150
01:34:46,080 --> 01:34:52,480
really simple, but amazing is this app called 
Flighty. You heard of it? F-L-I-G-H-T-Y.

1151
01:34:52,480 --> 01:34:52,720
No.

1152
01:34:52,720 --> 01:34:59,920
It is a travel app and it manages all of 
your flight itineraries and your friends'  

1153
01:34:59,920 --> 01:35:06,040
itineraries. But the reason why I love it is it 
goes two or three clicks deeper than the average  

1154
01:35:06,040 --> 01:35:12,000
travel app or your airline app and it tells 
you when your inbound plane is running late,  

1155
01:35:12,000 --> 01:35:16,440
it helps you to understand where the gates on. 
My wife was just in Madrid last week. And she  

1156
01:35:16,440 --> 01:35:20,440
texted me saying, "Hey, I'm at the airport but 
no gate is announced." I looked at Flighty,  

1157
01:35:20,440 --> 01:35:24,880
I'm like, "Your gate is E67. It's actually been 
assigned but it hasn't been announced." And this  

1158
01:35:24,880 --> 01:35:28,640
happens a lot in Europe. You'll be there and they 
won't tell you the gate until an hour beforehand. 

1159
01:35:28,640 --> 01:35:33,520
So it gives you so much information right 
before. It's actually publicly announced,  

1160
01:35:33,520 --> 01:35:37,600
which is really helpful, especially if 
you really need to be somewhere because  

1161
01:35:37,600 --> 01:35:41,920
oftentimes I know if my plane's going to be late 
and if I need to rebook before anyone else does,  

1162
01:35:41,920 --> 01:35:45,600
which helps you, gives you a better chance 
of getting somewhere. Or I will be able to  

1163
01:35:45,600 --> 01:35:49,480
get to a gate, I get to SFO and it 
might not be on the board at SFO,  

1164
01:35:49,480 --> 01:35:52,880
but I know exactly where it gave you this. So 
really a great app. Can't say enough about it.

1165
01:35:52,880 --> 01:35:56,680
I'm downloading it right now. 
It's got a bazillion reviews,  

1166
01:35:56,680 --> 01:36:01,310
five stars. Thank you for the 
recommendation. Incredibly useful.

1167
01:36:01,310 --> 01:36:01,320
Of course.

1168
01:36:01,320 --> 01:36:05,360
I'm trying out a new question. You've 
joined a bunch of different companies.  

1169
01:36:05,360 --> 01:36:10,960
What's one thing that you've done in the first 
90 days at the job that has made a big impact?

1170
01:36:10,960 --> 01:36:19,240
I go and I sit in team meetings and see how they 
operate. I just listen. I talk to not only the PMs  

1171
01:36:19,240 --> 01:36:28,120
but the content designer and everyone, and I try 
to get to know them by both name and story. And  

1172
01:36:28,120 --> 01:36:31,880
what I mean by that, it's like oftentimes 
people, execs come in and they're like,  

1173
01:36:31,880 --> 01:36:36,080
what are we doing? What are we prioritizing? 
Why does it matter? And they don't really take  

1174
01:36:36,080 --> 01:36:42,480
the time to actually learn who the people are, 
what the story is, what they care about, what  

1175
01:36:42,480 --> 01:36:49,320
they're passionate about, both professionally and 
personally and really try to understand how the  

1176
01:36:49,320 --> 01:36:53,880
team is working from that person's perspective.
And what I find is actually when I do that,  

1177
01:36:53,880 --> 01:37:00,680
people are way more willing to hear ... 
When it is time for me to share my thoughts,  

1178
01:37:00,680 --> 01:37:05,280
they're way more invested because 
they believe I'm invested in that.

1179
01:37:05,280 --> 01:37:11,080
